'''Amicus Therapeutics''' is a public American [[biopharmaceutical]] company based in [[Cranbury, New Jersey]].<ref name="10K2014" />{{rp|2}}  The company [[Initial public offering|went public]] in 2007 under the [[NASDAQ]] trading symbol FOLD.<ref>{{cite news | title=Amicus Therapeutics IPO raises $75 mln, in range | date=30 May 2007 | agency=Reuters | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2007/05/31/amicustherapeutics-ipo-idUSWEN848220070531 | deadurl=no<!--added to archive.org--> }}</ref>  This followed a 2006 planned offering and subsequent withdrawal, which would have established the trading symbol as AMTX<ref>{{cite news | title=Amicus Therapeutics files $86M IPO | author=Gelsi, Steve | work=[[MarketWatch]] | date=17 May 2006 | url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/amicus-therapeutics-files-86m-ipo | deadurl=no<!--added to archive.org--> }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Moyer, Liz | title=IPOs Head For The Exits | date=16 Aug 2006 | work=[[Forbes]] | url=https://www.forbes.com/2006/08/15/ipo-offerings-pulled-cx_lm_0816ipo.html | deadurl=no<!--present in archive.org--> | quote=There have been five withdrawn IPOs so far this month, including ... Amicus Therapeutics.  }}</ref>  Prior to their IPO, Amicus was funded by a variety of [[Venture capital financing|venture capital]] firms including [[Radius Ventures]], Canaan Partners and [[New Enterprise Associates]].<ref name="rubin2006">{{cite news | author=Rubin, Evelyn | title=Amicus IPO: A Very Risky Prospect (AMTX) | work=[[Seeking Alpha]] | date=18 May 2006 | url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/10870-amicus-ipo-a-very-risky-prospect-amtx | deadurl=no<!--present in archive.org--> }}</ref>

==History==
The therapeutic focus of Amicus is on [[Rare disease|rare and orphan diseases]], particularly disorders collectively called [[Lysosomal storage disease|lysosomal storage disorders]].<ref name="10K2014" />{{rp|2}}  The company has focused on [[pharmacological chaperone]]s and [[enzyme replacement therapy]].<ref name="10K2014" />{{rp|2,18}}<ref name="williams2014">{{cite book | author=Williams, Cory | editor=Pryde, David C. | editor2=Palmer, Michael J. | title=Orphan Drugs and Rare Diseases | chapter=Chapter 4. Treating Rare Diseases: Business Model for Orphan Drug Development | publisher=[[Royal Society of Chemistry]] | year=2014 | ISBN=9781849738064 }}</ref>{{rp|95}}

In 2008, the company expanded from its single site in New Jersey to a second research site in [[San Diego]].<ref name="biotechweek2008">{{cite news | title=Amicus Therapeutics Opens Research Facility in San Diego. | author=Staff | date=1 Oct 2008 | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-185777890.html | work=[[Biotech Week]] | location=United States | via=[[HighBeam Research]] }}</ref>

In late 2009, the company faced a major financial setback with the termination of a multi-year collaboration agreement with [[Shire (pharmaceutical company)|Shire]] for its lead compound, [[migalastat]], and two other products.<ref name="10Q2009Q3">{{cite web | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1178879/000095012309057623/c91935e10vq.htm | title=Form 10-Q: Amicus Therapeutics, Inc. | date=30 Sep 2009 | publisher=[[USSEC]] | website=[[EDGAR]] }}</ref>{{rp|24}}  Amicus cut 20% of its workforce.<ref name="10Q2009Q3" />{{rp|24}}

The next year, the company signed an exclusive license agreement with [[GlaxoSmithKline]] for miglastat; GSK paid $60 million in upfront and equity payments while promising up to $170 million to help developother products,<ref name="carroll2013">{{cite news | author=Carroll, John | title=GlaxoSmithKline politely dumps $230M Fabry drug deal with Amicus | date=20 Nov 2013 | work=FierceBiotech | url=http://www.fiercebiotech.com/story/glaxosmithkline-politely-dumps-230m-fabry-drug-deal-amicus/2013-11-20 }}</ref> GSK terminated the arrangement in 2013.<ref name="carroll2013" />

In November 2013, Amicus acquired competitor Callidus Biopharma for its enzyme replacement therapy treatment for [[Pompe disease]].<ref name="10K2014" />{{rp|3,12}}

In September 2015, the company acquired [[Scioderm]] for $229 million in cash and stock, with potentially $618 million more in [[biodollar]]s. Scioderm had a drug in Phase III trials for [[epidermolysis bullosa]]; additionally, if the drug was approved the FDA would give its owner a [[priority review voucher]], which itself can be sold to another company.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fidler|first1=Ben|title=Xconomy: With $229M Deal, Amicus Gets a New Drug And Perhaps a Voucher|url=https://www.xconomy.com/new-york/2015/08/31/with-229m-deal-amicus-gets-a-new-drug-and-maybe-a-voucher/?single_page=true|work=Xconomy|date=31 August 2015}}</ref>  That drug failed its Phase III trial in 2017 and Amicus abandoned it. It had paid out around half of the milestones to Scioderm's shareholders prior to closing down the program.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Phil|title=Amicus ditches skin disorder drug after late-stage failure|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/amicus-ditches-skin-disorder-drug-after-late-stage-failure|work=FierceBiotech|date=September 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref>

Also in September 2015, Amicus announced that it would submit a [[new drug application]] (NDA) for [[Accelerated approval (FDA)|accelerated approval]] of [[migalastat]] to the FDA by the end of 2015.<ref name="NDA">{{cite news|url=https://www.drugs.com/nda/migalastat_150915.html|publisher=[[Drugs.com]]|title=Amicus Therapeutics Plans to Submit NDA for Migalastat for Fabry Disease Following Positive Pre-NDA Meeting With FDA|date=15 September 2015}}</ref>  An FDA committee recommended approval in April 2016, but the FDA rejected the application in November for having insufficient data in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Ben|title=FDA rejects quick Amicus Fabry drug read-through, new data not expected till 2019|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/fda-rejects-quick-amicus-fabry-drug-read-through-new-data-not-expected-til-2019|work=FierceBiotech|date=November 29, 2016|language=en}}</ref>  The drug was approved in the European Union in May 2016.<ref name="Newswire">{{cite news|url=https://globenewswire.com/news-release/2016/05/31/844646/0/en/Amicus-Therapeutics-Announces-European-Commission-Approval-for-Galafold-Migalastat-in-Patients-with-Fabry-Disease-in-European-Union.html|title=Amicus Therapeutics Announces European Commission Approval for Galafold (Migalastat) in Patients with Fabry Disease in European Union|publisher=GlobeNewswire|date=31 May 2016}}</ref>  

In 2016 Amicus acquired MiaMed which was working on drugs to treat [[CDKL5]] deficiency; Amicus paid $1.8M in cash and around $4.7M in stock, with $83M in biodollars.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Ben|title=Amicus spends $90M on MiaMed; gains rare disease preclinical program|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/amicus-spends-90m-miamed-gains-rare-disease-preclinical-program|work=FierceBiotech|date=July 7, 2016|language=en}}</ref>

After [[Scott Gottlieb]] became FDA commissioner in 2017, the CEO of Amicus began lobbying him directly for the FDA to accept the NDA and in February 2018 the FDA accepted it and promised a response by August 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=John|title=Once rejected, FDA now rolls out a short red carpet for Amicus’ migalastat|url=https://endpts.com/once-rejected-fda-now-rolls-out-a-short-red-carpet-for-amicus-migalastat/|work=Endpoints|date=February 12, 2018}}</ref>

In September 2018, Amicus announced that it had acquired Celenex, which had ten early stage gene therapies. Amicus paid $100 million upfront and could pay an additional $352 million if developmental milestones are achieved.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/matthewherper/2018/09/20/a-100-million-biotech-deal-is-also-a-tale-of-two-executives-facing-their-kids-deadly-diseases/#6ee26df82aad|title=A $100 Million Biotech Deal Is Also A Tale Of Two Executives Facing Their Kids' Deadly Diseases|last=Herper|first=Matthew|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-09-24|language=en}}</ref> 

